The name is deliberate: unboxd-agency, because the agency was always
the point — "cloud" described where the work ran; "agency" describes
who the work serves and what the box becomes when identity and
governance are added to the artifact. The agent had the agency all
along; the org name now says so. The identity, canonically stated:
unboxd is the canonical open cloud agency — *open* as in
open-enterprise (everything open, but commercial), *cloud* as the
territory served rather than the name worn, *agency* in both its
senses at once: the firm that acts for its principals, and the quality
its boxes gain when identity and governance are added to the artifact.
The qualifiers compete and all of them are true — open (the posture:
everything open, but commercial), hybrid (the reach: every fabric,
every premises, every provider), serverless (the architecture: no
server anyone pets, state in the record, compute summoned by the
event) — and because each is a property rather than the point, none is
the name. Hence the resolution: unboxd is the canonical cloud agency.
Canonical does the work the qualifiers were auditioning for — the
definitive one, the one others are measured against, the reference
implementation of what a cloud agency is — and the properties (open,
hybrid, serverless, governed, evidenced) are what canon *means* here,
listed in the record rather than crowded into the title.
